{{Main|Hopewell tradition}} This is a '''list of Hopewell sites'''. The '''Hopewell tradition''' (also incorrectly called the "Hopewell culture") refers to the common aspects of the [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] culture that flourished along rivers in the northeastern and midwestern [[United States]] from 200 BCE to 500 CE. The Hopewell tradition was not a single [[culture]] or society, but a widely dispersed set of related populations that were connected by a common network of trade routes,<ref name="Price">{{cite book | author= Douglas T. Price, and Gary M. Feinman | year= 2008 | title= Images of the Past, 5th edition | pages= 274–277 | location= New York | publisher=McGraw-Hill | isbn= 978-0-07-340520-9}}</ref> known as the Hopewell Exchange System. <!--Please keep list alphabetized when editing--> <!--Please search list carefully before adding a site to avoid duplication, also add alternative spellings without wikilinks and point them to existing articles, avoid piped links if possible so that readers are aware of actual article titles when doing future edits--> {|class="wikitable sortable" style="width:98%" ! width="18%"|'''Site''' ! width="13%"|'''Image''' ! width="69%"|'''Description''' |- | [[Bynum Mound and Village Site]] || [[File:Mounds.jpg|125px|Bynum Mound and Village Site]] || Located near [[Houston, Mississippi]], the site is a complex of six conical shaped mounds which were in use during the Miller 1 and Miller 2 phases of the [[Miller culture]](100 BCE to 100 CE).<ref name="Pharr Mounds-Ceramic analysis">{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/history/history/online_books/natr/pharr_mounds-bear_creek/sec4-1.htm|title=Pharr Mounds-Ceramic analysis|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2010-11-16}}</ref><ref name=ENCYCPREHIST>{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Prehistory:North America|volume=6|edition=1|article=Middle Eastern Woodland|page=331|editor1-link=Peter N. Peregrine|editor1-first=Peter Neal|editor1-last=Peregrine|editor2-link=Melvin Ember|editor2-first=Melvin|editor2-last=Ember|publisher=Springer Publishing|year=2003|isbn=978-0-306-46264-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=edXSLIEpWOoC&pg=PA331&lpg=PA331&dq=bynum+mounds&source=bl&ots=ppxhpb1-8E&sig=nboo8563mPkOW0zm_4vsPFbYS24&hl=en&ei=3bXiTI20DYWKlwedi6XdAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBIQ6AEwADgU#v=onepage&q=bynum%20mounds&f=false}}</ref> and was built between 100 BCE and 100 CE. It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1989 as part of the [[Natchez Trace Parkway]] at milepost 232.4. |- | [[Cloverdale archaeological site]] || || The Cloverdale archaeological site (23BN2) is an important archaeological site near [[Saint Joseph, Missouri|St. Joseph, Missouri]]. It is located at the mouth of a small valley that opens into the [[Missouri River]]. It was occupied by [[Kansas City Hopewell]] (ca. 100 to 500 CE) peoples.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://users.stlcc.edu/mfuller/cloverdale/|title=Cloverdale Archaeological Site|accessdate =2009-10-09}}</ref> |- | [[Crooks mound]] || || A [[Marksville culture]] mound site, located in [[La Salle Parish, Louisiana]]. It is a large, conical, [[burial mound]] that was part of at least six episodes of burials. It measures about {{convert|16|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=mid|high}} and {{convert|85|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=mid|wide}}. |- | [[Dunns Pond Mound]] || [[File:Dunns Pond Mound.jpg|125px|Dunns Pond Mound]] || The Dunns Pond Mound is a historic [[tumulus|Native American mound]] in northeastern [[Logan County, Ohio|Logan County]], [[Ohio]], [[United States]]. Located near [[Huntsville, Ohio|Huntsville]], it lies along the southeastern corner of [[Indian Lake (Ohio)|Indian Lake]] in [[Washington Township, Logan County, Ohio|Washington Township]]. In 1974, the mound was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] as a potential [[archaeology|archeological]] site. |- | [[Fortified Hill Works]] || [[File:Fortified Hill Works Squier and Davis Plate VI.jpg|125px|Fortified Hill Works]] || Registered historic site near [[Hamilton, Ohio]]. |- | [[Fort Ancient (Lebanon, Ohio)]] || [[File:Ancient monuments fort ancient map.gif|125px|Fort Ancient (Lebanon, Ohio)]] || Fort Ancient is a collection of mounds and earthen walls located in [[Washington Township, Warren County, Ohio|Washington Township]], [[Warren County, Ohio]], along the eastern shore of the [[Little Miami River]], about seven miles (11&nbsp;km) southeast of [[Lebanon, Ohio|Lebanon]] on State Route 350. The site is the largest prehistoric hilltop enclosure in the United States, with three and one-half miles ({{convert|18,000|ft|m|abbr=on|disp=or}}) of walls in a {{convert|100|acre|km2|adj=on}} complex. |- | [[Grand Gulf Mound]] || || An Early [[Marksville culture]] site located near [[Port Gibson, Mississippi|Port Gibson]] in [[Claiborne County, Mississippi]], on a bluff {{convert|1|mi|km}} east of the [[Mississippi River]], {{convert|2|mi|km}} north of the mouth of the [[Big Black River (Mississippi)|Big Black River]]. The site has an extant burial mound, and it may have had two others in the past.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Brookes|first=Samuel O.|authorlink = |title=The Grand Gulf Mound: Salvage Excavation of an Early Marksville Burial Mound in Claiborne County, Mississippi |publisher=Mississippi Department of Archives and History|year= 1976|location= Jackson, Mississippi|pages= |series=Mississippi Archaeological Survey Report|isbn= }}</ref> |- | [[Hopeton Earthworks]] || [[File:Hopeton Work Squier and Davis Plate XVII.jpg|125px|Hopeton Earthworks]] || The Hopeton Earthworks are an Ohio Hopewell group of mounds and earthworks located about a mile east of the [[Hopewell Culture National Historical Park|Mound City group]] on a terrace of the [[Scioto River]]. The walls have been damaged by cultivation. They are contained in a detached portion of Hopewell Culture National Historic Park. |- | [[Hopewell Culture National Historical Park]] || [[File:Mound City Chillicothe Ohio HRoe 2008.jpg|125px|Mound City Group]] || Hopewell Culture National Historical Park, formerly known as Mound City Group National Monument, is a [[United States]] [[national historical park]] with [[Earthworks (archaeology)|earthworks]] and burial [[tumulus|mounds]] from the [[Hopewell culture]], indigenous peoples who flourished from about 200 BCE to 500 CE. The park is composed of five separate sites in [[Ross County, Ohio]]. The park includes [[archaeology|archaeological]] resources of the Hopewell culture. |- | [[Indian Mound Cemetery]] || [[File:Indian Mound Cemetery Romney WV 2005 09 16 02.jpg|125px|Indian Mound Cemetery]] || Indian Mound Cemetery is a [[cemetery]] located along the [[Northwestern Turnpike]] ([[U.S. Route 50 in West Virginia|U.S. Route 50]]) on a bluff overlooking the [[South Branch Potomac River]] in [[Romney, West Virginia|Romney]], [[West Virginia]]. The cemetery is centered around a Hopewell mound. The mound measures seven feet high and about fifteen feet in diameter. It is the largest of the remaining mounds discovered in [[West Virginia]]'s [[Eastern Panhandle of West Virginia|Eastern Panhandle]]. The city has never allowed the mound to be excavated. The [[Smithsonian Institution]] suggests this mound might date between 500 and 1000 CE and that it was likely constructed by peoples of the Hopewell culture. |- || [[Junction Group]] || Located near: 39.317045 -83.013619 || Earthworks site in [[Ross County, Ohio]]. |- | [[Kolomoki Mounds Historic Park]] || [[File:Kolomoki-temple-mound.jpg|125px|Kolomoki Mounds Historic Park]] || The Kolomoki Mounds are [[Woodland Period]] mounds built in [[Early County, Georgia|Early County]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. The seven mounds of earth at the site were built between 250-950 CE by [[Swift Creek culture|Swift Creek]] and [[Weeden Island culture|Weeden Island]] peoples. |- | [[Lake Ridge Island Mounds]] || [[File:Smaller Lake Ridge Island mound, eastern side.jpg|125px|Lake Ridge Island Mounds]] || The Lake Ridge Island Mounds (also known as the Wolf Mounds I-IV) are a group of small hills in [[Logan County, Ohio|Logan County]], [[Ohio]], [[United States]], that have been thought to be [[tumulus|Native American mounds]]. Located in an area of about {{convert|5|acre}} at the northern end on Lake Ridge Island in [[Indian Lake (Ohio)|Indian Lake]], the mounds are near the village of [[Russells Point, Ohio|Russells Point]] in the southeastern corner of [[Stokes Township, Logan County, Ohio|Stokes Township]]. |- | [[Leake Mounds]] || [[File:Leake Mounds site 2015.JPG|125px|Leake Mounds]] || Leake Mounds is an [[archaeological site]] in [[Bartow County, Georgia]], built and used by peoples of the [[Swift Creek Culture]]. |- | [[Lewiston Mound]] || [[File:Lewiston Mound Jun 09.JPG|125px|Lewiston Mound]] || A burial mound located at [[Lewiston, New York]], in [[Niagara County, New York]], on the grounds of the [[Earl W. Brydges Artpark State Park]]. |- | [[Mann Site]] || || The Mann Site (12 Po 2) is located in [[Posey County, Indiana]], and was placed on the National Historic Register in 1974.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/in/Posey/state.html|title=National Register of Historic Places-Indiana, Posey County|accessdate =2009-12-31}}</ref> |- | [[Marietta Earthworks]] || [[File:MariettaMoundsOldDrawing.jpg|125px|Marietta Earthworks]] || Located at the confluence of the Muskingum and Ohio Rivers in [[Washington County, Ohio]], under the modern day city of Marietta. The site once consisted of at least four large platform mounds, three walled enclosures, and a large burial mound, now the site of the [[Mound Cemetery (Marietta, Ohio)|Mound Cemetery]].<ref name=ROMAIN1>{{cite book| author = Romain, William F. |title= Mysteries of the Hopewell |date= 2000-10-01 |publisher= [[The University of Akron Press]] | pages= 129–142 | isbn= 978-1884836619 }}</ref> |- | [[Marksville Prehistoric Indian Site]] || [[File:Marksville State Historic Site Burial Mound.jpg|125px|Marksville Prehistoric Indian Site]] || Also known as the [[Marksville State Historic Site]], it is the [[type site]] for the [[Marksville culture]] and is located about one mile southeast of [[Marksville, Louisiana]]. |- | [[Moorehead Circle]] || || A triple [[henge|woodhenge]] constructed about two millennia ago at the [[Fort Ancient (Lebanon, Ohio)|Fort Ancient]] Earthworks in [[Ohio]]. |- | [[Mounds State Park]] || [[File:Mounds SP 1.jpg|125px|Mounds State Park]] || Mounds State Park is a state park in [[Anderson, Indiana]], featuring prehistoric [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] heritage, and 10 ceremonial mounds built by the [[Adena culture|Adena]] people and apparently also used by later [[Hopewell culture|Hopewell]] inhabitants. |- | [[Newark Earthworks]] || [[File:Ohio Newark Great Circle09.jpg|125px|Newark Earthworks]] || In [[Newark, Ohio]], the site consists of three sections of preserved [[Earthworks (archaeology)|earthwork]]: the Great Circle Earthworks, the Octagon Earthworks, and the Wright Earthworks. This complex was the largest earthen enclosure in the world. The site is preserved as a state park by the [[Ohio Historical Society]]. |- | [[Oak Mounds]] || || Outside [[Clarksburg, West Virginia]], in [[Harrison County, West Virginia|Harrison County]], a large Indian [[mound]]; to the west of it is a smaller mound. These mounds have never been totally excavated but they were probably built by the [[Hopewell culture]] between 0 and 1000 CE. |- | [[Pharr Mounds]] || [[File:Pharr Mounds.jpg|125px|Pharr Mounds]] || Located near [[Tupelo, Mississippi|Tupelo]] in parts of [[Itawamba County, Mississippi|Itawamba]] and [[Prentiss County, Mississippi]], a complex of eight dome-shaped burial mounds. The site was in use during the Miller 1 phase of the [[Miller culture]]<ref name="Pharr Mounds-Ceramic analysis"/> and was built between 1 and 200 CE. It is considered to be one of the largest and most important sites from this era.<ref name=PHARR-NPS>{{Cite web|title=Pharr Mounds-National Register of Historic Places Indian Mounds of Mississippi Travel Itinerary|publisher=National Park Service|url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/mounds/pha.htm|accessdate=2010-11-16}}</ref> |- | [[Portsmouth Earthworks]] || [[File:Portsmouth Works Group A B C D Squier and Davis 01.jpg|125px|Portsmouth Earthworks]] || The Portsmouth Earthworks is a large mound complex constructed by the [[Hopewell tradition#Ohio Hopewell culture|Ohio Hopewell culture]] (100 BCE to 500 CE).<ref name="ohiohistorycentral.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.ohiohistorycentral.org/entry.php?rec=2222|title=Portsmouth Earthworks-Ohio History Central|accessdate =2009-06-06}}</ref> The site was one of the largest ceremonial centers constructed by the Hopewell and is located at the confluence of the [[Scioto River|Scioto]] and [[Ohio River]]s. The majority of the site is now covered by the city of [[Portsmouth, Ohio|Portsmouth]] in [[Scioto County, Ohio]].<ref name="ohiohistorycentral.org"/> |- | [[Renner Village Archeological Site]] || || The Renner Village Archeological Site is a significant [[Kansas City Hopewell]] culture archaeological site located in the municipality of [[Riverside, Missouri]]. Known by archaeologists as the Renner site(23PL1), the site contains [[Hopewell tradition|Hopewell]] and [[Mississippian culture|Middle Mississippian]] artifacts. The site is one of a several Kansas City Hopewell sites near the junction of [[Line Creek (Missouri)|Line Creek]] and the [[Missouri River]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://users.stlcc.edu/mfuller/renner/|title=Renner Site 23PL1|accessdate =2009-10-09}}</ref> |- | [[Seip Earthworks and Dill Mounds District]] || [[File:Seip Earthworks Hopewell Culture NHP NPS.jpg|125px|Seip Earthworks and Dill Mounds District]] || A large hilltop enclosure in [[Ross County, Ohio]]. |- | [[Serpent Mounds Park]] || || Not to be confused with the [[Serpent Mound]] in [[Adams County, Ohio]], the site was constructed by the [[Point Peninsula Complex]] peoples, a Hopewellian people who lived in central and southeastern [[Ontario]], southwestern [[Quebec]], and northern parts [[New York state]] between 300 BCE and 700 CE. |- | [[Sinnissippi Mounds]] || [[File:Sterling Il Sinnissippi Site5.jpg|125px|Sinnissippi Mounds]] || The Sinnissippi Mounds are a [[Havana Hopewell culture]] burial mound grouping located in the city of [[Sterling, Illinois]], [[United States]]. |- | [[Toolesboro Mound Group]] || [[File:Toolesboro mounds.jpg|125px|Toolesboro Mound Group]] || A [[Havana Hopewell culture]] site, The Toolesboro Mound Group is a group of mounds on the north bank of the [[Iowa River]] near its discharge into the [[Mississippi River|Mississippi]]. The mounds are owned and displayed to the public by the [[State Historical Society of Iowa]]. The mound group is located east of [[Wapello, Iowa]], near the unincorporated community of [[Toolesboro, Iowa|Toolesboro]]. |- | [[Tremper Mound and Works]] || [[File:Tremper Mound Squier and Davis 01.jpg|125px|Tremper Mound and Works]] || The Tremper Mound and Works are an [[Hopewell tradition|Ohio Hopewell]] (100 BCE to 500 CE) earthen enclosure and large, irregularly shaped mound. It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1972. The site is located in [[Scioto County, Ohio]], about five miles northwest of [[Portsmouth, Ohio]], on the second terrace floodplain overlooking the [[Scioto River]]. |- | [[Trowbridge Archeological Site]] || || The '''Trowbridge Archaeological Site''' is located in the vicinity of North 61st Street and Leavenworth Road in [[Kansas City, Kansas]]. It was inhabited c. 200–600 CE by the [[Kansas City Hopewell]] culture. |- |}
