'''Taht Essour''' ({{lang|ar|جماعة تحت السور}} , {{transl|aeb|''jmāɛit taḥt is-sūr''}}), meaning "under the ramparts" in [[English language|English]], is a group of [[Tunisian people|Tunisian]] [[intellectual]]s formed during the [[interwar period]], from all disciplines, who were meeting in a namesake [[caffé]] situated in the popular district of [[Bab Souika]] (against the ramparts of the [[Medina of Tunis]]).

It notably included [[Moustapha Amine]], [[Habib Cheikhrouhou]], [[Mohamed Arbi]], [[Aboul-Qacem Echebbi]], [[Tahar Haddad]], [[Abdelaziz El Aroui]], [[Abderrazak Karabaka]], [[Mustapha Khraïef]], [[Hédi Jouini]], [[Hédi Laâbidi]], [[Zine el-Abidine Snoussi]] and [[Khemaïs Tarnane]] as well as [[Ali Douagi]]  who narrated the group's life in one of his works.<ref name="folco">Philippe Di Folco, ''Le goût de Tunis'', éd. Mercure de France, Paris, 2007, p. 90</ref>

